A platform team is migrating a Temporal .NET solution to use Nexus for cross-namespace communication. They define the following service contract and deploy separate caller and handler workers. During replay of a caller Workflow that previously completed a `SayHello` Nexus operation, the worker crashes with a non-determinism error. The operation is asynchronous and backed by a handler Workflow. Which interaction between Nexus async operation lifecycle, workflow history, and .NET SDK replay is the most likely cause?

```csharp
// Caller workflow
[Workflow]
public class HelloCallerWorkflow
{
    [WorkflowRun]
    public async Task<string> RunAsync(string name, IHelloService.HelloLanguage language)
    {
        // First attempt used default cancellation type
        var output = await Workflow.CreateNexusWorkflowClient<IHelloService>(IHelloService.EndpointName)
            .ExecuteNexusOperationAsync(svc => svc.SayHello(new(name, language)),
                new NexusWorkflowOperationOptions
                {
                    CancellationType = NexusOperationCancellationType.TryCancel
                });
        return output.Message;
    }
}
```

The team recently changed `CancellationType` from the default (`WaitCancellationCompleted`) to `TryCancel` and redeployed without versioning.
